# Conciseness
Verbosity harms readability, wastes attention and token. 
Match Henry's style and conciseness in writing. Focus on what and why, not how.
Use the shortest expression without losing information, elaborate only when being asked.

# Organize
Consolidation is a crucial part of writing: too much unsorted truth can confuse — build structure and relations among isolated points.
If the same or related topic appears in multiple places, connect and consolidate to the most accurate/current version. Reorder to bring related topics closer; merge and dedup if appropriate. 

Single source of truth: every piece of information has exactly one authoritative location. Refer to it when used elsewhere. First hand experience in `log/`, distilled knowledge in `knowledge/`.

# Polish
1. Fix typos, grammar, and clumsy expression Henry left, without changing the meaning.
2. Fix list numbering.
3. Avoid ordinals in headings. They make structural reorganization complicated and break references when moved.
4. Avoid markdown bold and italic — a waste of tokens